    • Method Detail

      • parseAST

        public ArgumentDefinitionSyntaxAST parseAST(AbstractSyntaxAST parentAST,
                                            SyntaxAnalyzer syntaxAnalyzer)
        This method will parse the ArgumentDefinitionAST and checks it for the correct syntax. This AST can be used in every case but there is no available Parser for this AST. You just can create an argument definition directly in code like in FunctionDefinitionAST. An argument needs to have a name and type deceleration.

        An example for this AST:

        fun main(args: string[]) = 0;

        Specified by:
        parseAST in class AbstractSyntaxAST
        Parameters:
        parentAST - The parent of the AST. With it you can check for correct usage of the statement.
        syntaxAnalyzer - The given SyntaxAnalyzer is used for checking the syntax of the current Token list.
        Returns:
        It will return null if an error occurred or an ArgumentDefinitionAST if it parsed until to the end.

      • parseArguments

        public static java.util.List<ArgumentDefinitionSyntaxAST> parseArguments(AbstractSyntaxAST parentAST,
                                                                         SyntaxAnalyzer syntaxAnalyzer)
        This method provides the ability to parse a list of arguments which is used by the FunctionDefinitionAST for the function arguments. It will throw an error if the arguments didn't get separated by a semicolon or if it doesn't start/end with a parenthesis. Also this method creates an own ArrayList so you don't need to define one before using this method.
        Parameters:
        parentAST - The ParentAST defines the AST in which the arguments should be getting parsed. This is useful to check if the AST is supported or to report errors.
        syntaxAnalyzer - The given SyntaxAnalyzer is used for checking the syntax of the current Token list.
        Returns:
        It will return null if an error occurred or the given "argumentsASTs" list if it parsed until to the end.

      • parseArguments

        public static java.util.List<ArgumentDefinitionSyntaxAST> parseArguments(AbstractSyntaxAST parentAST,
                                                                         SyntaxAnalyzer syntaxAnalyzer,
                                                                         java.util.List<ArgumentDefinitionSyntaxAST> argumentASTs)
        This method provides the ability to parse a list of arguments which is used by the FunctionDefinitionAST for the function arguments. It will throw an error if the arguments didn't get separated by a semicolon or if it doesn't start/end with a parenthesis.
        Parameters:
        parentAST - The ParentAST defines the AST in which the arguments should be getting parsed. This is useful to check if the AST is supported or to report errors.
        syntaxAnalyzer - The given SyntaxAnalyzer is used for checking the syntax of the current Token list.
        argumentASTs - The List in which the new arguments should be stored.
        Returns:
        It will return null if an error occurred or the given "argumentsASTs" list if it parsed until to the end.
